node.text: 🙇‍♀️ Our humble @canyonmtbracing  team is coming together. Feeling so fortunate and grateful we could pull this off during a time that has been uncertain for many. The fact that we are able to travel and race when many amateur sports are on hold is not something we take for granted. Lot’s of heavy lifting, and we are making progress. I think we win the coolest van award 😜 #CanyonMTBracing #BikeLife

node.text:
This past weekend saw many athletes compete in Mountain Bike World Championships, including me. I see many XCO racers expressing disappointment in themselves lately, particularly in the women's field, including myself. I've never raced with tears in my eyes, so this weekend was a first. But if I could write a message to my younger self and the other women out there, it would go something like this: 

 Despite your efforts and time, and energy invested into achieving your best performance possible, there can only be one winner. Whether your 70th or 1st place, you should know that your result does not define who you are or necessarily how hard you have or haven't worked. Your effort defines your character, and that's the beauty of sport. We learn, grow, achieve, love, fall, get back up, and do it all over again. Look adversity in the face and find the small wins. Focus on the process and grow through the highs and lows. The most beautiful thing about sport is becoming a better person through your efforts. You may not see it today, and you may struggle tomorrow, but if you look in the right places, you will see the good (or bad) in everything you do, and through that process, you will become better in sport and, most importantly, in life. 
🎥 @pango_visual 
@canyonmtbracing

So proud to be part of this 💙 @Canyon  From 25-29 August, the attention of the entire mountain biking world will be drawn towards two highlight events on the MTB calendar. The UCI World Championships in Val di Sole, Italy, and the Audi Nines in Germany.
•
And normally, we’d be lighting up the bikes of our @canyon_cllctv pros with special artwork in the riders’ national colours, or wild designs to stand out from the crowd.
•
But this time round, we’re doing things differently. To make an important statement: for unity, for the global riding community, for the sport. By marking the bike of every CLLCTV athlete with the same message, proudly displayed on the down tube. ONE WORLD.
•
A positive message, inspired by a positive idea. That we’re all here on this planet together, and we’re all part of the same awesome global cycling community. Especially in our modern world, unity and solidarity are more important than ever. Canyon’s aim is clear: to inspire mountain bikers worldwide to grow, progress, and preserve the sport we love for every and any cyclist. Together we are part of One World, and part of One Collective. We are all together. 
•
To underline this moment, Canyon are calling on the MTB community to join them in making a difference. How? By supporting the amazing work being done by World Bicycle Relief, an organisation committed to helping more people across the planet gain access to bicycles, and the countless opportunities they present. It’s the worthiest of worthy causes. And we’re backing it whole-heartedly – that’s why every donation made through our fundraising page also give you the chance of winning an exclusive Spectral CF 29 with the same Canyon ‘One World’ artwork as our athletes’ bikes.
•
Find the link to donate to World Bicycle Relief in the linkinbio.
•
#MyCanyon #OneWorldOneCLLCTV #MTB #CanyonCLLCTV
